{"add":{"doc":{"id":"761f4250adb579c82354fbaa4d0b78a8b60dc1bb0a0fb5fc23ff6c72cc994bf1","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a0/Casanova_ritratto.jpg/170px-Casanova_ritratto.jpg","previous":[],"after":["Venice has long been a source of inspiration for authors, poets and playwrights as well as being at the forefront of the technical developing of printing and publishing.","Two of the most famous Venetian writers were Marco Polo in the Middle Ages and later Giacomo Casanova. Polo (1254–1324) was a merchant who voyaged to the Orient. His series of books, co-written by Rustichello da Pisa, titled Il Milione provided important knowledge of the lands east of Europe, from the Middle East, to China, Japan and Russia. Giacomo Casanova (1725–1798) was a prolific writer and famous adventurer best remembered for his autobiography, Histoire De Ma Vie (Story of My Life), which links his colourful lifestyle to the city of Venice."]}}}